mber-that-wed-all-rather-forget/\">hard-hitting news</a> with their coverage of the protests going on downtown and just how the righteously indignant dress these days.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0.1pt 0in; text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0.1pt 0in; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: trebuchet ms,geneva; font-size: large;\">On Wall Street, people are upset that America&rsquo;s a big money-grabbing capitalist and that the assholes on Wall Street are assholes, so they&rsquo;re staging a good ole-fashioned &ldquo;occupation&rdquo;: the &ldquo;Occupy Wall Street&rdquo; protesters &ldquo;occupy&rdquo; Zuccotti Park, whic they have been &ldquo;occupying&rdquo; since Sept. 17th.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0.1pt 0in; text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0.1pt 0in; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: trebuchet ms,geneva; font-size: large;\">Flannel and<strong> Doc Martens</strong>, unsurprisingly, are very popular, as is a wanton disregard for good grooming. However, one protester interviewed deeply considered the various factors of her environment and situation before getting dressed:&nbsp;&nbsp;&ldquo;I&rsquo;m wearing heels and they&rsquo;re really comfortable. I kind of didn&rsquo;t plan to be protesting. I mean what&rsquo;s a protest outfit? Like in case you get maced or arrested? You have to think about the elements and the forces that come up against you. The pencil skirt is vintage I got at a thrift store. My gauzy shirt I just got the other day and I&rsquo;ve worn it maybe four times already. The sunglasses are <strong>Michael Kors</strong>.&rdquo;</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0.1pt 0in; text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin: 0.1pt 0in; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: trebuchet ms,geneva; font-size: large;\">Thank you! Someone knows how to dress for an act of nonviolent disapprobation; and when in doubt &mdash; designer.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"