><span style=\"font-size: medium;\">I love blind dates. There is never any such thing as one that is regrettable.&nbsp; Drinking or eating with someone new for one night only, or making a new friend, or having a terrific new war story are the worst things that can happen (assuming whoever is setting you up was unaware of a criminal history and penchant). &nbsp;All of the above outcomes are pretty damn good.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: medium;\">So when one of my best friends emailed me to tell me she gave out my phone number, I was cool with it, as I always am.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: medium;\">&ldquo;He&rsquo;s got excellent credentials,&rdquo; she wrote. &ldquo;Multiple Ivy League degrees, a fat bank account, loves to travel, lives in your neighborhood and look at his picture! Cute!&rdquo; He was cute, indeed, and yep, he did seem like someone I could proudly take home to my parents: The guy sounded like all that and a bag of potato chips.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: medium;\">In person, however, the second Mr. Perfect Resume walked in and said hello, my gaydar pinged. That&rsquo;s fabulous&mdash;I love gay&mdash;but not when you&rsquo;re wearing a hetero jersey and you&rsquo;re out with me. Don&rsquo;t pretend to play for my team.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: medium;\">Worse, he was abrasive, argumentative and combative. I&rsquo;m all for good, witty banter, but not battle.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: medium;\">Fifteen minutes into our date, I was done. Closed. Shut down.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: medium;\">So what did I do?</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: medium;\">I sat captive on the dark, tufted couch and continued sipping my cocktail like a schmuck.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: medium;\">I put up with his pot shots, which peppered the otherwise scintillating conversation. He climbed Kilimanjaro! He&rsquo;d been on safari! He&rsquo;s training to cross-country ski to the South Pole from the Antarctic! He is a restaurant and hotel investor!</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: medium;\">Nevertheless, he did not have my rapt attention.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: medium;\">I was in and out of Dreamland.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: medium;\">What would happen if I interrupted him to say, &ldquo;Hey, listen: I&rsquo;m gonna go. It&rsquo;s not really clicking here for me, but it&rsquo;s nice to have met you. Here&rsquo;s $20 for the cocktail.&rdquo; The delicious fantasy of freedom from simply being honest was so close I could taste it as well as my drink. Sofa, here I come.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: medium;\">But my politeness held me prisoner for a grand total of three hours.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: medium;\">Can you believe it?</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: medium;\">I was too worried about offending the prick to get up and go, even though he had no good social graces, himself, sharing such personal statements as, &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t UNDERSTAND women,&rdquo; and, &ldquo;Marriage is not about love!&rdquo; and, &ldquo;Strip clubs are great for the first two minutes,&rdquo; as well as other charming confessions throughout the night.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: medium;\">So with that date in mind, I am changing my M.O. and turning fantasy into reality.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: medium;\">If ever again I am in a similar situation, I&rsquo;m gone at the very moment it is wrong.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: medium;\">It&rsquo;s the era of Social Etiquette 2.0: Polite to Me.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: medium;\"><strong>e.b.k. &nbsp;lives, plays and dates in new york. her most recent blind date will not affect her continuing to happily accept new ones.</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: medium;\">What&rsquo;s your best exit line?</span><